<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="433" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="39.[115,1321,1515,2489]" pageId="39" pageNumber="433">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[116,812,2180,2213]" pageId="39" pageNumber="433">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
There is no specific information for this species, but the Mexican Least Shrew might be ecologically similar to the North American Least Shrew.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="433" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="39.[115,1321,1515,2489]" pageId="39" pageNumber="433">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[118,464,2298,2331]" pageId="39" pageNumber="433">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Not assessed on The IUCN Red List. The Mexican Least Shrew has a very restricted distribution (32,000 km?®) but does not seem to have any major threats; it is common in livestock pastures, implying it can withstand some habitat degradation. Additional research on ecology, threats, and taxonomy are needed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
